Vice President Mike Pence will be traveling to the Republic of Korea, Japan, Indonesia, Australia, and Hawaii from April 15-25, 2017. This will be his first official trip to the Asia-Pacific region. During his trip, he will emphasize President Trump's commitment to U.S. alliances and partnerships in the region, highlight the Administration's economic agenda, and show support for American troops. In South Korea, Pence will spend Easter Sunday with U.S. and South Korean troops and their families, participate in a bilateral meeting with Acting President Hwang Kyo-ahn, and meet with National Assembly Speaker Chung Sye-kyun. In Japan, he will meet with Prime Minister Shinzo Abe and lead the U.S.-Japan Economic Dialogue. He will also tour the USS Ronald Reagan and give remarks to U.S. and Japanese service members. In Indonesia, Pence will meet with President Joko Widodo, ASEAN Secretary General, and ASEAN Permanent Representatives. He will also participate in a listening session with U.S. and Indonesian business leaders. In Australia, he will meet with Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull, Foreign Minister Julie Bishop, and Opposition Leader Bill Shorten. He will also meet with U.S. and Australian service members and give remarks to the U.S. and Australian business community. The trip will conclude in Hawaii, where Pence will meet with senior leadership from the Pacific Command, visit the USS Arizona Memorial, and meet with U.S. troops and their families.